nd moral techniques of recognition and cultural translation that emerge in response to these social uncertainties. In particular, Migrants in Translation focuses on Italian ethno-psychiatry as an emerging technique that provides culturally appropriate therapeutic services exclusively to migrants, political refugees, and victims of torture and trafficking. Cristiana Giordano argues that ethno-psychiatry’s focus on cultural identifications as therapeutic—inasmuch as it complies with current political desires for diversity and multiculturalism—also provides a radical critique of psychiatric, legal, and moral categories of inclusion, and allows for a rethinking of the politics of recognition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAssimilation (Sociology)xPsychological aspects. 0aAssimilation (Sociology)zItalyxPsychological aspects. 0aCultural pluralism. 0aEthnopsychologyxItaly. 0aEthnopsychologyzItaly. 0aImmigrantsxCultural assimilationxItaly. 0aImmigrantsxCultural assimilationzItaly. 0aImmigrantsxMental healthxItaly. 0aImmigrantsxMental healthzItaly. 0aMental health services. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095886940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958869/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles